{"title_page": "Deepan Sivaraman", "text_new": "{{Use Indian English|date= February 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=  February  2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name                = Deepan Sivaraman <br> \u0d26\u0d40\u0d2a\u0d7b \u0d36\u0d3f\u0d35\u0d30\u0d3e\u0d2e\u0d7b \n| image               = Deepan Sivaraman.jpg\n| caption             = Deepan Sivaraman in 2012\n| birth_name          = Deepan Sivaraman\n| native_name_lang    = ml\n| birth_place         = [[Thrissur]], [[Kerala]]\n| alma_mater          = [[Central Saint Martins]], [[Wimbledon College of Arts]]\n| occupation          = [[Theatre director]], [[scenographer]] and [[academic]]\n| website             = [http://www.oxygentheatre.in/ Oxygen Theatre Company]\n}}\n\n'''Deepan Sivaraman''' is an Indian [[theatre director]], [[scenographer]] and [[academic]].<ref name=\"Interview with Deepan Sivaraman\"/> He is the founder of [http://www.oxygentheatre.in/ Oxygen Theatre Company] based in Delhi. He is from [[Thrissur]], [[Kerala]]. \nSivaraman received Charles Wallace India Trust Award in 2003,<ref name=\"Charles Wallace India Trust Awards\">{{cite news|last1=Menon|first1=Anasuya|title=Wallace Route to Education|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/wallace-route-to-education/article2994764.ece|accessdate=7 September 2014|publisher=Hindu Group|date=March 14, 2012}}</ref> ''[[Kerala Sangeetha Nataka Akademi]] Award'' and ''[http://www.metawards.com/ Mahindra Excellence in Theatre Awards]'' in 2011 and 2010, respectively.<ref name=\"Interview with Deepan Sivaraman\">{{cite journal|last=Punjani|first=Deepa|title=Mrs|journal=Critical Stages|issue=June 2013: Issue 8|url=http://archive.criticalstages.org/criticalstages8/entry/ldquoThe-Future-of-Indian-Theatre-Will-Be-Based-on-Our-Ability-to-Intermingle-With-Other-Art-Disciplinesrdquo-mdash-Interview-with-Deepan-Sivaraman-Indian-Theatre-Director-and-Scenographer?category=3#sthash.nT9AB4lQ.dpbs}}</ref> Deepan served as the Artistic Director for the [https://web.archive.org/web/20141006072026/http://theatrefestivalkerala.com/itfok.php International Theatre Festival of Kerala](ITFOK) for 2014 edition which had a curatorial focus on transition, gender and spectatorship.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Ganesh|first1=Deepa|title=For Visual Language|journal=Frontline|date=April 18, 2014|url=http://www.frontline.in/arts-and-culture/for-visual-language/article5848123.ece#|accessdate=16 August 2014}}</ref> Deepan Sivaraman currently is an [[Associate Professor]] of [[Performance Studies]] at School of Culture and Creative Expressions at the [http://aud.ac.in/ Ambedkar University in Delhi].\n\n== Early life and career ==\n\nDeepan started his career as a carpenter in early 90s which helped him to pursue his [[theatre studies]] later on. After graduating from School of Drama Thrissur, [[Calicut University]] he undertook an MA in Performance practice at [[Pondicherry University]] and started practicing as a freelancer. Later he returned to academics and earned an MPhil degree in theatre from School of Letters from [[Mahatma Gandhi University, Kerala|Mahatma Gandhi University]] Kottayam. In 2003 he was awarded Charles Wallace India Trust Scholarship to study MA in [[Scenography]] at [[Central Saint Martins]] College of Arts and Design London. Following his graduation from CSM he worked as a Studio Tutor and Associate Lecturer at [[University of the Arts London]]-CSM until he moved to [[Wimbledon College of Art]] to pursue his Doctoral studies. He continued teaching scenography at Wimbledon College of Art until he returned to India in 2012.\n\nDuring his life in India and Europe he taught at many institutions as a visiting faculty teaching scenography and performance making. During the last 20 years of his theatre career he worked on several productions as a director and scenographer and some of the notable productions have travelled to festivals such as Edinburgh, Avignon, Almeda, ITFOK, BRM and META etc. He was honoured with [http://Sankeet%20Natak%20Akademi%20Award Sankeet Natak Akademi Award]{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} (Kerala) for theatre direction in 2012. His most famous play Spinal Cord received 10 nominations for [http://Mahindra%20Excellence%20Theatre%20Award Mahindra Excellence Theatre Award]{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} (META) and won seven awards including the best play of the year, best director and best scenographer. Along with his theatre colleagues he found [http://Oxygen%20Theatre%20Company Oxygen Theatre Company]{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} in 2008 based in Kerala.\n\n==''The Legend of Khasak'' [[Khasakkinte Itihasam]] \u2013 The Play a Milestone==\nDeepan involved with KM Kunjambu Smaraka Kalasamaithi.(KMK) Trikaripur for the project of ''The Legends of Khasak'' [[Khasakkinte Itihasam]] with the local village actors, it was a unique theatre project that has no similarities in the recent Indian theatre history in the terms of its production of working with village actors and the way in which the entire village got part of it. The trans \u2013 chronic post-modern novel of [[O. V. Vijayan]], ''The Legends of Khasak'' [[Khasakkinte Itihasam]] is revived onto the stage, in the Land of dark native myths and tantalizing legends \u2013 [[Kasaragod]]. The geographical memory of Khasak is transplanted to the landscape of Kasaragod. The tree of life, Revered Time, Slits of spreading self and sins and mythicized nature of Khasak takes a re-birth to burn down into the body ofspectator. The performance fuses native religious rituals and native art forms in separately. The three months of theatre camp for the regional artists were a refreshing wind to the cultural present of Kerala, which proved that the rural art gatherings were not extinct in the cultural space. From the last remaining sapling spread a green hope which rushed the village into a spring of artistic thought. There were muted tunes, silenced slogans and an unbroken harmony which united the whole village onto the theatre. Portraying, or interpreting Khasak into its multidimensional plurality was a challenge to any medium, to which this theatrical interpretation stands as an exemption. The characters of Khasak Allapicha Mollakka, Maimuna, Appukili, Naizam Ali, Kuttandan Pushari and Ravi meet the spectators in the aesthetically subverted, politically deconstructed, surreal space.<ref>https://indianexpress.com/article/lifestyle/art-and-culture/it-takes-a-village-2756713</ref><ref>https://malayalam.samayam.com/lifestyle/travel/khasakkinte-ithihasam-staged-at-kochi/articleshow/58329244.cms</ref><ref>https://www.manoramaonline.com/literature/interviews/2017/05/08/interview-with-deepan-sivaraman.html</ref>\n\n== Directorial works along with its design ==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|- \"\n! Year !! Title !! Credit\n|-\n| 2018||''Dark Things'' || Scenographer and co-director with Dr. Anuradha Kapur\n|-\n| 2018|| ''Nationalism Project'' || Director, Scenographer\n|-\n| 2015|| ''The Legends of Khasak'' || Director, Scenographer<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lal|first1=Amrith|title=It Takes a Village|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/lifestyle/art-and-culture/it-takes-a-village-2756713/|accessdate=22 July 2016|publisher=Indian Express|date=17 April 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2015|| ''The Cabinet of Dr Caligari'' || Director, Scenographer<ref name=\"Master of Dark Arts\">{{cite news|last1=Nath|first1=Dipanitha|title=Mrs|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/entertainment-others/master-of-the-dark-arts/|accessdate=30 June 2015|publisher=Indian Express|date=8 February 2015|ref=Master of Dark Arts}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2014|| ''It\u2019s Cold in Here'' || Director, Scenographer<ref>{{cite news|last1=Nath|first1=Dipanita|title=A play on sexual violence will take you into a discomfort zone|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/lifestyle/i-want-you-to-feel-the-pain-of-the-performance/|accessdate=10 August 2014|agency=The Indian Express|publisher=The Indian Express|date=August 7, 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2014|| ''Project Nostalgia'' || Director, Scenographer<ref>{{cite web|title=Project Nostalgia - a theatre performance|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HfncRlwPYVE|date=22 April 2014|website=[[youtube.com]]|publisher=AUD Institutional Memory Project|access-date=25 January 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2013|| '' The Little Prince'' || Director, Scenographer\n|-\n| 2011|| '' Ubu Roi'' || Director, Scenographer & Dramaturge<ref name=\"Skeletons in The Kings Cupboard\">{{cite news|last1=Nath|first1=Dipanitha|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/cities/delhi/national-award-inshallah-football-ashvin-kumar-film-on-social-causeskeletons-in-the-kings-cupboard/|title=National Award,Inshallah Football,Ashvin Kumar,Film on Social CauseSkeletons in the King's Cupboard|accessdate=30 June 2015|publisher=The Indian Express|date=8 May 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2010|| '' Peer Gynt Director'' || Scenographer, Dramaturge<ref name=\"Deep Into theatre\">{{cite news|last1=Nair|first1=Shilpa|title=Deep into Theatre|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/deep-into-theatre/article916164.ece|accessdate=8 June 2014|date=2010-11-27}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2009|| '' Spinal Cord'' || Director, Scenographer & Dramaturge<ref>{{cite web|title=A study in scenography|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/magazine/article441053.ece?service=print|accessdate=15 August 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2004|| '' The circle of the seasons'' || Director, Scenographer \n|-\n| 2004|| '' Dream of Death'' || Director, Scenographer \n|-\n| 2002|| '' Kamala'' || Director, Scenographer<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sadanandan|first1=Smitha|title=Woman redifined|url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/mp/2002/06/17/stories/2002061701420200.htm|accessdate=8 June 2014|date=2002-06-17|ref=Kamala}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1998|| '' Lord of the Flies'' || Director, Dramaturge\n|-\n|}\n[[File:Ubu Roi-2012 Scenography& Direction Deepan Sivaraman. Produced by National School of Drama Delhi.JPG|thumb|right|Ubu Roi-National School of Drama Delhi(2012)]][[File:Peer Gynt-2010 Scenography& Direction Deepan Sivaraman. Produced by Oxygen Theatre Company Kerala.jpg|thumb|right|Peer Gynt-Produced by Oxygen Theatre Company Kerala(2010)]][[File:Spinal Cord - 2009 Scenography& Direction Deepan Sivaraman. Produced by Oxygen Theatre Company Kerala.jpg|thumb|right|Spinal Cord-Produced by Oxygen Theatre Company(2009)]]\n\n== Scenography works==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|- \"\n! Year !! Title !! Director!! Producer\n|-\n| 2018|| ''The Girl in the Drain'' || Dr. Anuradha Kapur || National School of Drama Delhi\n|-\n| 2017|| ''Naked Voices''|| Neelam Mansingh Chowdhry || National School of Drama Delhi\n|-\n| 2016|| ''Talatum'' || [[Abhilash Pillai]]  || Serendipity Art Trust Delhi \n|-\n| 2016|| ''Bitter Fruit'' || Neelam Mansingh Chowdhry || National School of Drama Delhi<ref>{{cite news|last1=Utpal K|first1=Banarjee|title=Method to Madness|url=http://www.dailypioneer.com/vivacity/method-to-madness.html|accessdate=22 July 2015|publisher=The Pioneer|date=2015-05-18|ref=Bitter Fruit}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2012|| ''Virasat'' || Dr. Anuradha Kapur || National School of Drama Delhi.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Utpal K|first1=Banarjee|title=Epic of the ordinary|url=http://www.dailypioneer.com/vivacity/epic-of-the-ordinary.html|accessdate=8 June 2014|publisher=The Pioneer|date=2013-05-28|ref=Virasat}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2008|| ''The Little India'' || Emily Grey || Trestle Theatre, UK \n|-\n| 2006|| ''Palm Grove Tales'' || [[Abhilash Pillai]] || School of Drama Thrissur \n|-\n| 2003|| ''Siddartha'' || Jyothish MG|| Abhinaya Theatre Centre Thiruvananthapuram\n|-\n| 2002|| ''Bhagvadujjukeeyam'' || Jyothish MG|| Abhinaya Theatre Centre Thiruvananthapuram\n|-\n| 2001|| ''Verdigris'' ||[[Abhilash Pillai]]  || Abhinaya Theatre Centre Thiruvananthapuram\n|-\n| 2000|| ''Thatri Realizing Self'' || J Shailaja || Kriya Collective Thiruvananthapuram \n|-\n|}\n\n== Major Theatre Festivals participated==\n\n* 2019 \u2013 [[International Theatre Festival of Kerala]] Kerala, Dark Things\n* 2018 \u2013 Wuzhen International Theatre Festival Shanghai, The Cabinet of Dr Caligari\n* 2018 \u2013 YULICA International theatre festival Krakow, Nationalism Project.\n* 2017 \u2013 International Theatre Festival of Kerala 9th Edition, The Cabinet of Dr Caligari\n* 2016 \u2013 International Theatre Festival of Kerala 8th Edition, The Legends of Khasak\n* 2016 \u2013 Bharat Rang Mahotsav Delhi, The Cabinet of Dr Caligari\n* 2013 \u2013 International Theatre Festival of Kerala 7th Edition, Virasat\n* 2012 \u2013 International Theatre Festival [[National School of Drama]] Delhi, Peer Gynt\n* 2011 \u2013 International Theatre Festival of Kerala 5th Edition, Peer Gynt\n* 2011 \u2013 National theatre Festival of Kerala, Peer Gynt\n* 2010 \u2013 Ibsen Festival New Delhi, Peer Gynt\n* 2010 \u2013 Mahindra Excellence in theatre Awards New Delhi, Spinal Cord\n* 2010 \u2013 Rangayana National Theatre Festival Bangalore, Spinal Cord\n* 2009 \u2013 International Theatre Festival National School of Drama Delhi, Spinal Cord\n* 2009 \u2013 International Theatre Festival of Kerala, Spinal Cord\n* 2009 \u2013 National Theatre Festival Thiruvananthapuram Kerala, Spinal Cord\n* 2007 \u2013 Avignon Theatre Festival France, Siddhartha\n* 2006 \u2013 [[Prithvi Theatre]] Festival Mumbai, Bagavdajjukam\n* 2006 \u2013 South Asian Theatre Festival New Delhi, Siddhartha\n* 2004 \u2013 International Theatre Festival National School of Drama New Delhi, Siddhartha\n* 2003 \u2013 International Theatre Festival National School of Drama Delhi, Bagavadajjukam\n* 2001 \u2013 International Theatre Festival National School of Drama New Delhi, Verdigris\n* 2000 \u2013 Festival De Alameda Lisbon Portugal, Verdigris\n* 2000 \u2013 Asian Woman Theatre Festival New Delhi, Thathri Realising Self\n\n== Awards ==\n*2010 \u2013 '''''Mahindra Excellence in Theatre Awards'''''<ref name=\"A study in scenography\">{{cite news|last1=Ramunath|first1=Renu|title=A study in scenography|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/magazine/article441053.ece?service=print|accessdate=8 June 2014|publisher=Indian Express|date=2010-06-20}}</ref>\n*2012 \u2013 '''''Kerala Sangeet Nataka Akademi Award'''''<ref>{{cite web| title=Sangeetha Nataka Akademi awards announced|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-kerala/sangeetha-nataka-akademi-awards-announced/article2791885.ece|accessdate=8 June 2014|publisher=The Hindu|date=11 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sivaraman, Deepan}}\n[[Category:Indian theatre directors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Theatre practitioners]]\n[[Category:Indian drama teachers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Pondicherry University alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Indian English|date= February 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=  February  2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name                = Deepan Sivaraman <br> \u0d26\u0d40\u0d2a\u0d7b \u0d36\u0d3f\u0d35\u0d30\u0d3e\u0d2e\u0d7b \n| image               = Deepan Sivaraman.jpg\n| caption             = Deepan Sivaraman in 2012\n| birth_name          = Deepan Sivaraman\n| native_name_lang    = ml\n| birth_place         = [[Thrissur]], [[Kerala]]\n| alma_mater          = [[Central Saint Martins]], [[Wimbledon College of Arts]]\n| occupation          = [[Theatre director]], [[scenographer]] and [[academic]]\n| website             = [http://www.oxygentheatre.in/ Oxygen Theatre Company]\n}}\n\n'''Deepan Sivaraman''' is an Indian [[theatre director]], [[scenographer]] and [[academic]].<ref name=\"Interview with Deepan Sivaraman\"/> He is the founder of [http://www.oxygentheatre.in/ Oxygen Theatre Company] based in Delhi. He is from [[Thrissur]], [[Kerala]]. \nSivaraman received Charles Wallace India Trust Award in 2003,<ref name=\"Charles Wallace India Trust Awards\">{{cite news|last1=Menon|first1=Anasuya|title=Wallace Route to Education|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/wallace-route-to-education/article2994764.ece|accessdate=7 September 2014|publisher=Hindu Group|date=March 14, 2012}}</ref> ''[[Kerala Sangeetha Nataka Akademi]] Award'' and ''[http://www.metawards.com/ Mahindra Excellence in Theatre Awards]'' in 2011 and 2010, respectively.<ref name=\"Interview with Deepan Sivaraman\">{{cite journal|last=Punjani|first=Deepa|title=Mrs|journal=Critical Stages|issue=June 2013: Issue 8|url=http://archive.criticalstages.org/criticalstages8/entry/ldquoThe-Future-of-Indian-Theatre-Will-Be-Based-on-Our-Ability-to-Intermingle-With-Other-Art-Disciplinesrdquo-mdash-Interview-with-Deepan-Sivaraman-Indian-Theatre-Director-and-Scenographer?category=3#sthash.nT9AB4lQ.dpbs}}</ref> Deepan served as the Artistic Director for the [https://web.archive.org/web/20141006072026/http://theatrefestivalkerala.com/itfok.php International Theatre Festival of Kerala](ITFOK) for 2014 edition which had a curatorial focus on transition, gender and spectatorship.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Ganesh|first1=Deepa|title=For Visual Language|journal=Frontline|date=April 18, 2014|url=http://www.frontline.in/arts-and-culture/for-visual-language/article5848123.ece#|accessdate=16 August 2014}}</ref> Deepan Sivaraman currently is an [[Associate Professor]] of [[Performance Studies]] at School of Culture and Creative Expressions at the [http://aud.ac.in/ Ambedkar University in Delhi].\n\n== Early life and career ==\n\nDeepan started his career as a carpenter in early 90s which helped him to pursue his [[theatre studies]] later on. After graduating from School of Drama Thrissur, [[Calicut University]] he undertook an MA in Performance practice at [[Pondicherry University]] and started practicing as a freelancer. Later he returned to academics and earned an MPhil degree in theatre from School of Letters from [[Mahatma Gandhi University, Kerala|Mahatma Gandhi University]] Kottayam. In 2003 he was awarded Charles Wallace India Trust Scholarship to study MA in [[Scenography]] at [[Central Saint Martins]] College of Arts and Design London. Following his graduation from CSM he worked as a Studio Tutor and Associate Lecturer at [[University of the Arts London]]-CSM until he moved to [[Wimbledon College of Art]] to pursue his Doctoral studies. He continued teaching scenography at Wimbledon College of Art until he returned to India in 2012.\n\nDuring his life in India and Europe he taught at many institutions as a visiting faculty teaching scenography and performance making. During the last 20 years of his theatre career he worked on several productions as a director and scenographer and some of the notable productions have travelled to festivals such as Edinburgh, Avignon, Almeda, ITFOK, BRM and META etc. He was honoured with [http://Sankeet%20Natak%20Akademi%20Award Sankeet Natak Akademi Award]{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} (Kerala) for theatre direction in 2012. His most famous play Spinal Cord received 10 nominations for [http://Mahindra%20Excellence%20Theatre%20Award Mahindra Excellence Theatre Award]{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} (META) and won seven awards including the best play of the year, best director and best scenographer. Along with his theatre colleagues he found [http://Oxygen%20Theatre%20Company Oxygen Theatre Company]{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} in 2008 based in Kerala.\n\n==''The Legend of Khasak'' [[Khasakkinte Itihasam]] \u2013 The Play a Milestone==\nDeepan involved with KM Kunjambu Smaraka Kalasamaithi.(KMK) Trikaripur for the project of ''The Legends of Khasak'' [[Khasakkinte Itihasam]] with the local village actors, it was a unique theatre project that has no similarities in the recent Indian theatre history in the terms of its production of working with village actors and the way in which the entire village got part of it. The trans \u2013 chronic post-modern novel of [[O. V. Vijayan]], ''The Legends of Khasak'' [[Khasakkinte Itihasam]] is revived onto the stage, in the Land of dark native myths and tantalizing legends \u2013 [[Kasaragod]]. The geographical memory of Khasak is transplanted to the landscape of Kasaragod. The tree of life, Revered Time, Slits of spreading self and sins and mythicized nature of Khasak takes a re-birth to burn down into the body ofspectator. The performance fuses native religious rituals and native art forms in separately. The three months of theatre camp for the regional artists were a refreshing wind to the cultural present of Kerala, which proved that the rural art gatherings were not extinct in the cultural space. From the last remaining sapling spread a green hope which rushed the village into a spring of artistic thought. There were muted tunes, silenced slogans and an unbroken harmony which united the whole village onto the theatre. Portraying, or interpreting Khasak into its multidimensional plurality was a challenge to any medium, to which this theatrical interpretation stands as an exemption. The characters of Khasak Allapicha Mollakka, Maimuna, Appukili, Naizam Ali, Kuttandan Pushari and Ravi meet the spectators in the aesthetically subverted, politically deconstructed, surreal space.<ref>https://indianexpress.com/article/lifestyle/art-and-culture/it-takes-a-village-2756713</ref><ref>https://malayalam.samayam.com/lifestyle/travel/khasakkinte-ithihasam-staged-at-kochi/articleshow/58329244.cms</ref><ref>https://www.manoramaonline.com/literature/interviews/2017/05/08/interview-with-deepan-sivaraman.html</ref>\n\n== Directorial works along with its design ==   \n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|- \"\n! Year !! Title !! Credit\n|-\n| 2018||''Dark Things'' || Scenographer and co-director with Dr. Anuradha Kapur\n|-\n| 2018|| ''Nationalism Project'' || Director, Scenographer\n|-\n| 2015|| ''The Legends of Khasak'' || Director, Scenographer<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lal|first1=Amrith|title=It Takes a Village|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/lifestyle/art-and-culture/it-takes-a-village-2756713/|accessdate=22 July 2016|publisher=Indian Express|date=17 April 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2015|| ''The Cabinet of Dr Caligari'' || Director, Scenographer<ref name=\"Master of Dark Arts\">{{cite news|last1=Nath|first1=Dipanitha|title=Mrs|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/entertainment-others/master-of-the-dark-arts/|accessdate=30 June 2015|publisher=Indian Express|date=8 February 2015|ref=Master of Dark Arts}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2014|| ''It\u2019s Cold in Here'' || Director, Scenographer<ref>{{cite news|last1=Nath|first1=Dipanita|title=A play on sexual violence will take you into a discomfort zone|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/lifestyle/i-want-you-to-feel-the-pain-of-the-performance/|accessdate=10 August 2014|agency=The Indian Express|publisher=The Indian Express|date=August 7, 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2014|| ''Project Nostalgia'' || Director, Scenographer<ref>{{cite web|title=Project Nostalgia - a theatre performance|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HfncRlwPYVE|date=22 April 2014|website=[[youtube.com]]|publisher=AUD Institutional Memory Project|access-date=25 January 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2013|| '' The Little Prince'' || Director, Scenographer\n|-\n| 2011|| '' Ubu Roi'' || Director, Scenographer & Dramaturge<ref name=\"Skeletons in The Kings Cupboard\">{{cite news|last1=Nath|first1=Dipanitha|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/cities/delhi/national-award-inshallah-football-ashvin-kumar-film-on-social-causeskeletons-in-the-kings-cupboard/|title=National Award,Inshallah Football,Ashvin Kumar,Film on Social CauseSkeletons in the King's Cupboard|accessdate=30 June 2015|publisher=The Indian Express|date=8 May 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2010|| '' Peer Gynt Director'' || Scenographer, Dramaturge<ref name=\"Deep Into theatre\">{{cite news|last1=Nair|first1=Shilpa|title=Deep into Theatre|url=http://www