{"title_page": "Ong-ard Satrabhandhu", "text_new": "{{autobiography|date=August 2017}}\n\n{{copypaste|url=http://ongardarchitects.com/profile|date=August 2017}}\n{{copypaste|url=http://ongardarchitects.com/projects/rachamankha|date=August 2017}}\n\n{{Infobox architect\n| name = Ong-ard Satrabhandhu\n| image = ong-ard.jpg\n| nationality = Thai\n| significant_buildings = Rachamankha, Kiatnakin Bank\n| significant_projects = One Nimman\n| awards = Richard H. Driehaus Prize 2020\nNational Artist of Thailand 2009 <br>The Baird Prize, Cornell University 1962 <br>The York Prize, Cornell University 1960\n| alma_mater = [[Yale University]]<br> [[Cornell University]]\n| website = http://ongardarchitects.com\n| practice = \n}}\n\n'''Ong-ard Satrabhandhu''' is an [[architect]] from Thailand. His style is known for linking the classical and traditional architecture languages of East and West. Currently, he is involved in the planning and architectural design of external envelope of \u201cOne Nimman\u201d Urban development project in Chiang Mai, Thailand. Ong-ard Satrabhandhu was awarded the renowned [[Driehaus Architecture Prize]] in 2020.\n\n== Career ==\nOng-ard received his B. Arch from [[Cornell University]] in 1965 and M. Arch from [[Yale University]] in 1967<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archinect.com/news/bustler/7646/ong-ard-satrabhandhu-named-as-2020-driehaus-prize-laureate|title=Ong-ard Satrabhandhu named as 2020 Driehaus Prize laureate|website=Archinect|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>. At Cornell he studied under [[Colin Rowe]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Arkaraprasertkul|first=Non|last2=Rabitaille|first2=Reilly Paul|date=2009-01|title=Differences, Originality and Assimilation: Building Nine at Panabhandhu School|url=https://www.mitpressjournals.org/doi/abs/10.1162/thld_a_00202|journal=Thresholds|language=en|volume=35|pages=8\u201315|doi=10.1162/thld_a_00202|issn=1091-711X}}</ref>\n\nDuring his career, Ong-ard helped bring recognition to the traditional [[Lanna]] buildings and temples through his style and by being a defender and advocate for preservation.\n\nOne of his best known work is [http://rachamankha.com/ Rachamankha] which is an allusion to the Chiang Mai temple architecture<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hubbell|first=Diana|url=https://www.theguardian.com/travel/2016/mar/26/chiang-mai-guide-thailand-activities-hotels-restaurants-bars|title=Chiang Mai, Thailand, guide: what to do, plus the best hotels and restaurants|date=2016-03-26|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-10|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>. The courtyard model is exploited for its inward-looking, and \u2014 in a hot, humid climate \u2014 provides oases for the public and private spaces. Constructed with materials such as clay tiles and turned teak columns, is a reference to the courtyard houses of China and Nepal.\n\nThe book of his work, \"[http://www.rizzoliusa.com/book.php?isbn=9780847844876 A Tradition of Serenity: The Tropical Houses of Ong-ard Satrabhandhu\"] was published in 2015.\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery widths=\"250\" heights=\"250\">\nFile:Ong-ard Architects Capriccio.jpg|Ong-ard Architects Capriccio\nFile:On 06.jpg|One Nimman\nFile:On 09.jpg|One Nimman\nFile:On 01.jpg|One Nimman Drawing\nFile:On 13.jpg|One Nimman\nFile:Toshiba_Headquater.jpg| Toshiba Thailand Headquarters, Bangkok, Thailand \nFile:Kiatnakin Elevation.jpg|Kiatnakin Bank\nFile:Kb 3.jpg|Kiatnakin Bank, Bangkok Chinatown\nFile:Tb 2.jpg|Tin Baron Hotel\nFile:Rachamankha Sala.jpg|Rachamankha : Fran\u00e7ois Halard\nFile:Rachamankha 2.jpg|Rachamankha: Fran\u00e7ois Halard\nFile:Three-family Residence.jpg|Three-family Residence: Fran\u00e7ois Halard\nFile:Mae Rim Residence.jpg|Mae Rim Residence: Micheal Freeman\nFile:Tamarind Village 2.jpg|Tamarind Village: Fran\u00e7ois Halard\n</gallery>\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://archinect.com/news/bustler/7646/ong-ard-satrabhandhu-named-as-2020-driehaus-prize-laureate Ong-ard Satrabhandhu named as 2020 Driehaus Prize laureate]\n*[https://architecturehereandthere.com/2017/05/07/thai-architect-ong-ard-krier/ Architecture Here and There, ''The Apotheosis of Ong-ard,'' May 2017]\n* [http://thresholds.mit.edu/issue/thresholds_35.pdf Thresholds Journal MIT, ''Differences, Originality and Assimilation: Building Nine at Panabhandhu School,'' 2009]\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/07/travel/07iht-lanna.1.5595665.html The New York Times, ''The Struggle to Save Classic Thai Architecture,'' 2007]\n* [http://art4d.com/2017/01/silence-of-the-past Art 4d, ''Silence of the Past,'' February 2000]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{Driehaus Prize laureates}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ong-ard Satrabhandhu}}\n[[Category:Driehaus Architecture Prize winners]]\n[[Category:Thai architects]]\n[[Category:National Artists of Thailand]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:New Classical architects]]\n", "text_old": "{{autobiography|date=August 2017}}\n\n{{copypaste|url=http://ongardarchitects.com/profile|date=August 2017}}\n{{copypaste|url=http://ongardarchitects.com/projects/rachamankha|date=August 2017}}\n\n{{Infobox architect\n| name = Ong-ard Satrabhandhu\n| image = ong-ard.jpg\n| nationality = Thai\n| significant_buildings = Rachamankha, Kiatnakin Bank\n| significant_projects = One Nimman\n| awards = Richard H. Driehaus Prize 2020\nNational Artist of Thailand 2009 <br>The Baird Prize, Cornell University 1962 <br>The York Prize, Cornell University 1960\n| alma_mater = Yale University<br> Cornell University\n| website = http://ongardarchitects.com\n| practice = \n}}\n\n'''Ong-ard Satrabhandhu''' is an [[architect]] from Thailand. His style is known for linking the classical and traditional architecture languages of East and West. Currently, he is involved in the planning and architectural design of external envelope of \u201cOne Nimman\u201d Urban development project in Chiang Mai, Thailand. Ong-ard Satrabhandhu was awarded the renowned [[Driehaus Architecture Prize]] in 2020.\n\n== Career ==\nOng-ard received his B. Arch from [[Cornell University]] in 1965 and M. Arch from [[Yale University]] in 1967<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archinect.com/news/bustler/7646/ong-ard-satrabhandhu-named-as-2020-driehaus-prize-laureate|title=Ong-ard Satrabhandhu named as 2020 Driehaus Prize laureate|website=Archinect|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>. At Cornell he studied under [[Colin Rowe]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Arkaraprasertkul|first=Non|last2=Rabitaille|first2=Reilly Paul|date=2009-01|title=Differences, Originality and Assimilation: Building Nine at Panabhandhu School|url=https://www.mitpressjournals.org/doi/abs/10.1162/thld_a_00202|journal=Thresholds|language=en|volume=35|pages=8\u201315|doi=10.1162/thld_a_00202|issn=1091-711X}}</ref>\n\nDuring his career, Ong-ard helped bring recognition to the traditional [[Lanna]] buildings and temples through his style and by being a defender and advocate for preservation.\n\nOne of his best known work is [http://rachamankha.com/ Rachamankha] which is an allusion to the Chiang Mai temple architecture<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hubbell|first=Diana|url=https://www.theguardian.com/travel/2016/mar/26/chiang-mai-guide-thailand-activities-hotels-restaurants-bars|title=Chiang Mai, Thailand, guide: what to do, plus the best hotels and restaurants|date=2016-03-26|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-10|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>. The courtyard model is exploited for its inward-looking, and \u2014 in a hot, humid climate \u2014 provides oases for the public and private spaces. Constructed with materials such as clay tiles and turned teak columns, is a reference to the courtyard houses of China and Nepal.\n\nThe book of his work, \"[http://www.rizzoliusa.com/book.php?isbn=9780847844876 A Tradition of Serenity: The Tropical Houses of Ong-ard Satrabhandhu\"] was published in 2015.\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery widths=\"250\" heights=\"250\">\nFile:Ong-ard Architects Capriccio.jpg|Ong-ard Architects Capriccio\nFile:On 06.jpg|One Nimman\nFil