rict]].\n\nThe surname Abou Fadel comes from Sheikh Jabbour \"Abou Fadel\", the governor of [[Ain Aanoub]] at the time, who was named Abou Fadel due to the fact that his eldest son, born in the 1700s, was named Fadel. (Abou means father in Arabic)\n\n== Origins ==\nThe family is originally from the town of [[Izra|Izraa]] in the [[Daraa Governorate]] of [[Syria]].\nIn the year 1620, Sheikh Jubra'il (grandfather of Sheikh Jabbour \"Abou Fadel\") settled in [[Ain Aanoub]], [[Lebanon]].\n\nThe Abou Fadel family descends from [[Joktan|Qahtan]], the son of [[Eber|\u02bf\u0100bir]] ([[Hud (prophet)|H\u016bd]]), an ancestor of the [[Israelites]] and the [[Ishmaelites]] according to the [[Generations of Noah|Table of Nations]] in the Book of Genesis (Genesis 10-11). [[Joktan|Qahtan]] is originally from [[Yemen]].<ref>[https://www.britannica.com/biography/Qahtan]</ref>\n[[File:Qahtanites.png|550px|thumbnail|A family tree of the Qahtanites]]\n\nThe Abou Fadel family from [[Ain Aanoub]] is not related to the Abou Fadel family of [[Brummana]].\n\n== Prominent Members of the Abou Fadel family ==\n*[[Mounir Abou Fadel]] member of the Parliament of Lebanon from 1957 to 1987, and [[Deputy speaker of the Parliament of Lebanon|Deputy Speaker of the Parliament of Lebanon]].<ref>[https://military.wikia.org/wiki/Mounir_Abou_Fadel]</ref>\n*[[Marwan Abou Fadel]] former MP of Mount Lebanon, Co-Founder of the [[Lebanese Democratic Party]] and Secretary General of the Lebanese Orthodox Meeting.<ref>[https://www.lorientlejour.com/article/850197/marwan-abou-fadel-nouveau-secretaire-general-de-la-rencontre-orthodoxe.html Article in ''L'orient Le Jour'']</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Ain Aanoub]]\n*[[Qahtanite]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Lebanese families]]\n[[Category:Members of the Greek Orthodox Church of Antioch]]\n", "name_user": "Fakhreddine123", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abou_Fadel_family"}
{"title_page": "Adipaththar", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2016}}\n{{unreferenced|date=September 2011}}\n\n'''Adipatthar''' or '''Adhipattha Nayanar''' is one of the 63 [[Nayanmars]]. He was a sincere devotee of [[Shiva]] and lived in the [[Chola]] kingdom at present day [[Nagapattinam]] (referred in sangam literature as [[Naagai]]) by the sea shore.\n\n==Life==\nHe was the head of his group of people called Paradhavar. The main source of income and food for them was [[fish]] gotten from the [[sea]]. As a way of expressing love to God Siva, Adipatthar would toss the very first fish he earned every day back into the sea, [[wikt:offering#Noun|dedicating to God]]. He would practice this ritual even if he got just one fish on a day, thereby deciding to stay hungry for the entire night.\n'' Chekkizhar's Periya Puranam about Adipatthar: ''\n\n''\" The head of Paradhavarfor God. He then got a big golden fish one day which he gave to God happily and thus attained Lord forever\" ''\n\nThe dancing God of golden court decided to test his love and patience. Therefore, Adipatthar started to get just one fish for many consecutive days. Even then, the ardent devotee left them back to sea happily saying \"Let this be to Thy who is our father and Mother\". As a result, Adipatthar started becoming more and more poor. Days passed in the same way and one day his clan saw a miracle. They got a big golden fish filled with nine types of [[Gemstone|gems]] in their net. Adpatthar admired the fish and told \"This wonderful fish shines like the [[Sun]]. It is the first one we got today and we are blessed to give it back to Shiva\". He then left it back to the sea. Having felt his sincere love, the Lord who wears the crescent descended from the sky and blessed Adipatthar and his people saying \"Let you and your people be with me forever\". Adipatthar thus attained the glorious place near God Himself.\n\n{{Nayanars}}\n\n[[Category:Nayanars]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2016}}\n{{unreferenced|date=September 2011}}\n\n'''Adipatthar''' or '''Adhipattha Nayanar''' is one of the 63 [[Nayanmars]]. He was a sincere devotee of [[Lord Shiva]] and lived in the [[Chola]] kingdom at present day [[Nagapattinam]] (referred in sangam literature as [[Naagai]]) by the sea shore.\n\n==Life==\nHe was the head of his group of people called Paradhavar. The main source of income and food for them was [[fish]] gotten from the [[sea]]. As a way of expressing love to God Siva, Adipatthar would toss the very first fish he earned every day back into the sea, [[wikt:offering#Noun|dedicating to God]]. He would practice this ritual even if he got just one fish on a day, thereby deciding to stay hungry for the entire night.\n'' Chekkizhar's Periya Puranam about Adipatthar: ''\n\n''\" The head of Paradhavarfor God. He then got a big golden fish one day which he gave to God happily and thus attained Lord forever\" ''\n\nThe dancing God of golden court decided to test his love and patience. Therefore, Adipatthar started to get just one fish for many consecutive days. Even then, the ardent devotee left them back to sea happily saying \"Let this be to Thy who is our father and Mother\". As a result, Adipatthar started becoming more and more poor. Days passed in the same way and one day his clan saw a miracle. They got a big golden fish filled with nine types of [[Gemstone|gems]] in their net. Adpatthar admired the fish and told \"This wonderful fish shines like the [[Sun]]. It is the first one we got today and we are blessed to give it back to Shiva\". He then left it back to the sea. Having felt his sincere love, the Lord who wears the crescent descended from the sky and blessed Adipatthar and his people saying \"Let you and your people be with me forever\". Adipatthar thus attained the glorious place near God Himself.\n\n{{Nayanars}}\n[[Category:Nayanars]]\n", "name_user": "Titodutta", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adipaththar"}
